William Legge, 2nd Earl of Dartmouth, [PC](/Her_Majesty%27s_Most_Honourable_Privy_Council), [FRS](/Royal_Society) (born 20 June 1731 – died 15 July 1801), carried the courtesy title of Viscount Lewisham from 1732 until his succession to the earldom in 1750. He was a prominent [British statesman](/British_statesman) whose career intersected with one of the most tumultuous periods in imperial history. Most notably, he served as [Secretary of State for the Colonies](/Secretary_of_State_for_the_Colonies) from 1772 to 1775, a critical juncture that saw the rapid escalation of grievances leading directly to the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution). His tenure in this role placed him squarely at the heart of the burgeoning crisis between Great Britain and its North American colonies. Beyond his political contributions, Legge's legacy is also imprinted on the academic landscape, as he is the venerable namesake of [Dartmouth College](/Dartmouth_College), an institution he was instrumental in establishing, despite his later financial detachment.

### Early life

Born into the aristocratic Legge family, William Legge’s early life was marked by a significant loss and an early inheritance. He was the son of [George Legge, Viscount Lewisham](/George_Legge,_1st_Baron_Dartmouth), who, by a cruel twist of fate, predeceased his own father and passed away when William was merely one year old. This meant that the young William was destined to inherit the earldom directly from his grandfather. His mother was Elizabeth, the daughter of [Sir Arthur Kaye, 3rd Baronet](/Sir_Arthur_Kaye,_3rd_Baronet), grounding him further within the established gentry.

His formal education commenced in 1748 when he entered [Trinity College, Oxford](/Trinity_College,_Oxford). This was a typical path for young men of his standing, providing a grounding in classical studies and preparing them for a life of public service or landed gentry. Just two years later, in 1750, he formally succeeded his grandfather, William Legge, 1st Earl of Dartmouth, becoming the 2nd Earl. This elevation to the peerage at such a young age thrust him into the House of Lords and the political arena much earlier than many of his contemporaries.

Beyond his political and familial connections, Lord Dartmouth was also notable for his deep personal piety and evangelical leanings, a somewhat unusual trait for an aristocrat of his stature in the mid-18th century. It was his strong religious convictions that led him, in 1764, to act upon the suggestion of [Thomas Haweis](/Thomas_Haweis), a prominent evangelical clergyman. Dartmouth recommended [John Newton](/John_Newton), a former slave trader who had undergone a profound religious conversion and was seeking ordination, to [Edmund Keene](/Edmund_Keene), the then [Bishop of Chester](/Bishop_of_Chester). This intervention was crucial; despite Newton's controversial past and lack of traditional academic qualifications, Lord Dartmouth's endorsement was instrumental in securing Newton's acceptance for the [Anglican](/Anglican) ministry. Newton would, of course, go on to become a renowned abolitionist and the celebrated author of the hymn "[Amazing Grace](/Amazing_Grace)," a testament to Dartmouth's discerning patronage.

### Portrait of William Legge, 2nd Earl of Dartmouth

A striking visual record of William Legge, 2nd Earl of Dartmouth, exists in the form of a portrait painted by the esteemed Italian artist [Pompeo Batoni](/Pompeo_Batoni). This particular work, executed between 1752 and 1756, captures the Earl during his formative years, likely during a Grand Tour or shortly thereafter, reflecting the sophistication and gravitas expected of a young nobleman. The portrait is now a notable piece within the collection of the [Hood Museum of Art](/Hood_Museum_of_Art), which is itself located at [Dartmouth College](/Dartmouth_College) in [Hanover, New Hampshire](/Hanover,_New_Hampshire) – a fitting home, given the institution's namesake. Batoni was celebrated for his ability to convey both the social standing and the individual character of his sitters, and this portrait of Lord Dartmouth is no exception, offering a glimpse into the appearance and perhaps the temperament of the man who would play a significant role in British colonial affairs.

### Political career

Ah, the "political career." A grand phrase for navigating the labyrinthine corridors of power, often with less grace than one might hope. One might wish for more definitive documentation of the twists and turns, but alas, some periods remain shrouded in the convenient fog of history. For those who insist on *verifiable* information, it is noted that Lord Dartmouth's political ascent formally commenced with his appointment to the presidency of the [Board of Trade and Foreign Plantations](/Board_of_Trade). He held this significant position from 1765 to 1766, a period of burgeoning imperial complexity. The Board of Trade was a crucial administrative body responsible for overseeing colonial affairs, regulating commerce, and advising the Crown on matters concerning the vast and increasingly unruly overseas territories. His initial tenure, though brief, provided him with an intimate understanding of the colonial issues that would later define a more substantial portion of his public life.

#### Secretary for the Colonies

It was, however, his second, more impactful appointment that cemented his place in the annals of British history: [Secretary of State for the Colonies](/Secretary_of_State_for_the_Colonies). He assumed this demanding role on 27 August 1772, concurrently serving as [First Lord of Trade](/President_of_the_Board_of_Trade), and remained in office until 10 November 1775. This period, it must be stated, was nothing short of catastrophic for Anglo-American relations. Dartmouth found himself at the helm of colonial administration precisely as the simmering resentments across the Atlantic boiled over.

His time as Colonial Secretary was indelibly marked by the infamous [Boston Tea Party](/Boston_Tea_Party) in December 1773, an act of defiance that dramatically escalated tensions. In response to this audacious protest, Lord Dartmouth, along with the rest of [Lord North's](/Frederick_North,_Lord_North) government, firmly supported the punitive measures that followed. These included the series of acts collectively dubbed the "[Intolerable Acts](/Intolerable_Acts)" by the colonists, which aimed to reassert British authority by closing Boston Harbor, altering the Massachusetts charter, and allowing British officials accused of crimes to be tried in Britain. One might observe that such heavy-handed tactics rarely inspire loyalty, but rather, a more fervent desire for independence. He also supported the [Quebec Act](/Quebec_Act), which expanded the territory of Quebec, granted rights to French Catholics, and established French civil law, further inflaming Protestant colonists who saw it as a threat to their religious and political freedoms.

In his correspondence during this tumultuous period, Dartmouth grappled with the intricate challenges of colonial governance. For instance, in 1772, he exchanged letters with [Sir William Johnson, 1st Baronet](/Sir_William_Johnson,_1st_Baronet), the Superintendent of Northern Indian Affairs in America. Johnson, a key figure in British relations with [Indigenous peoples of the Americas](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas), advocated for new, consistent trade regulations with Native American tribes. Dartmouth, while acknowledging the validity and necessity of Johnson's arguments for a coherent imperial policy, expressed a weary recognition that the individual Colonies were far from inclined to concur with any unified approach. The inherent disunity and self-interest of the colonial assemblies, coupled with the vast distances involved, rendered effective central control a perpetual struggle – a problem that, one could argue, was entirely predictable.

As the conflict intensified, Dartmouth received numerous dispatches from [Josiah Martin](/Josiah_Martin), the royal governor of [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), throughout the summer of 1775. These letters painted a grim picture, detailing the desperate preparations the Loyalist government was undertaking to counter the burgeoning Patriot militia units and the escalating events of the revolution. The communications underscore the rapidly deteriorating situation, moving from political disagreements to open armed conflict, all under Dartmouth's watch.

Following his demanding tenure as Colonial Secretary, Lord Dartmouth transitioned to the role of [Lord Privy Seal](/Lord_Privy_Seal), serving from 1775 to 1782. This was a less hands-on administrative position, primarily involving the custody of the Privy Seal, which was affixed to important government documents. It allowed him to remain within the highest echelons of government, albeit in a capacity less directly responsible for the day-to-day management of the collapsing colonial empire.

Interestingly, Lord Dartmouth's initial arrival in the Colonies, before the full storm of revolution broke, was met with a rather different sentiment. It was celebrated by the pioneering African-American poet, [Phillis Wheatley](/Phillis_Wheatley), in her famous poem, "To the Right Honourable William, Earl of Dartmouth." Wheatley, herself a former slave, praised Dartmouth as a champion of liberty, expressing hopes that his appointment would bring an end to tyranny and safeguard the rights of all, including the enslaved. The bitter irony of these hopes against the backdrop of his later actions to suppress colonial liberty is, to put it mildly, rather profound.

### Philanthropy

It seems that even in the 18th century, some efforts to document charitable endeavors were… less than rigorous. One might infer that the sheer goodness of the act was expected to be its own citation, which, while charmingly naive, is hardly suitable for posterity. Nevertheless, the record, however sporadically sourced, reveals a significant philanthropic streak in Lord Dartmouth.

He was a substantial benefactor and the leading trustee for the English trust established to finance the creation of the [Moor's Charity School](/Moor%27s_Charity_School). This institution, founded in [Lebanon, Connecticut](/Lebanon,_Connecticut), by the tenacious [Eleazar Wheelock](/Eleazar_Wheelock), aimed to provide education and promote the [religious conversion](/Religious_conversion) of [Indigenous peoples of the Americas](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas). Dartmouth's involvement underscores his deep evangelical convictions, which extended beyond mere personal faith into active social betterment.

Indeed, Legge’s religious devotion was quite distinctive for an aristocrat of his era. He was a devout [Methodist](/Methodist), a movement often associated with the working classes and seen as unconventional by the established Anglican hierarchy. He regularly attended Methodist meetings in [Wednesbury](/Wednesbury), where his fellow Methodists – a diverse congregation comprising many [colliers](/Colliery) (coal miners) and [drovers](/Droving) (livestock drivers) – knew him affectionately as "Brother Earl." This willingness to engage with and support a movement that transcended rigid social stratification speaks volumes about his character and commitment to his faith, demonstrating a rare humility and genuine spiritual conviction that cut across the strict class divisions of 18th-century Britain.

It was Wheelock who, in a strategic move, subsequently founded [Dartmouth College](/Dartmouth_College) in [Hanover, New Hampshire](/Hanover,_New_Hampshire), explicitly naming the new institution in Lord Dartmouth's honour. The hope, quite transparently, was to secure ongoing and substantial financial support from the influential Earl. However, in a turn of events that might surprise some (or perhaps not, given the pragmatic nature of such endeavors), Lord Dartmouth ultimately refused to provide further significant financial backing for the college named after him. His initial involvement and the prestige of his name were clearly valuable, but his financial commitment did not extend to the new, ambitious collegiate venture.

Back in London, Lord Dartmouth was also a dedicated supporter of the new [Foundling Hospital](/Foundling_Hospital). This vital charitable institution was established for the care and maintenance of London's abandoned children, a pressing social issue of the time. He served as a vice-president of the organization from 1755 until his death, indicating a long-term commitment to its mission. His engagement with the Foundling Hospital also connects him to the artistic world, as the renowned painter [Sir Joshua Reynolds](/Joshua_Reynolds) painted the Earl's portrait and generously donated it to the hospital's collection. This significant artwork remains part of the Foundling Hospital Collection and can be viewed today at the [Foundling Museum](/Foundling_Museum) in London, serving as a tangible link between philanthropy, art, and social history.

In recognition of his intellectual pursuits and contributions, William Legge was admitted as a [Fellow of the Royal Society](/Fellow_of_the_Royal_Society) on 7 November 1754, an honor bestowed upon individuals who had made significant achievements in the natural sciences or demonstrated a keen interest in scientific advancement.

### Marriage and children

Ah, the bedrock of dynastic continuation and, occasionally, personal fulfillment. One trusts the details are sufficiently comprehensive, as these matters of lineage often prove terribly important to those who compile such records. For those who require exhaustive documentation, it should be noted that Lord Dartmouth entered into matrimony with Frances Catherine Nicholl on 11 January 1755. Frances was the daughter of [Sir Charles Gounter Nicoll](/Sir_Charles_Gounter_Nicoll), ensuring a union that reinforced his existing social standing. Their marriage was fruitful, producing a considerable progeny of nine children, ensuring the continuation of the Legge family line.

Their children included:

*   [George Legge, 3rd Earl of Dartmouth](/George_Legge,_3rd_Earl_of_Dartmouth) (born 3 October 1755, died 10 November 1810). As the eldest son, he naturally succeeded his father in the earldom.
*   Hon William Legge (born 4 February 1757).
*   Hon Charles Gounter Legge (born 18 May 1759).
*   Hon Heneage Legge (born 7 May 1761).
*   Hon Henry Legge (born 23 January 1765, died 19 April 1844).
*   [Admiral](/Admiral) [the Hon](/The_Honourable) Sir [Arthur Kaye Legge](/Arthur_Kaye_Legge) [KCB](/Order_of_the_Bath) (born 25 October 1766, died 12 May 1835). He achieved significant distinction in the Royal Navy, rising to the rank of Admiral.
*   [Rt Rev](/The_Right_Reverend) and Hon [Edward Legge](/Edward_Legge_(bishop)) (born 11 December 1767, died 27 January 1827). Following a career in the church, he became the esteemed [Bishop of Oxford](/Bishop_of_Oxford) from 1816 to 1827.
*   [The Ven](/The_Venerable) and Hon [Augustus George Legge](/Augustus_Legge_(archdeacon_of_Winchester)) (born 21 April 1773, died 1828). He also pursued an ecclesiastical career, serving as [Archdeacon of Winchester](/Archdeacon_of_Bournemouth) from 1814 to 1819.
*   Lady Charlotte Legge (born 5 October 1774, died 5 November 1848). She married [Charles Duncombe, 1st Baron Feversham](/Charles_Duncombe,_1st_Baron_Feversham), further cementing the family's connections within the British aristocracy.

### Death

William Legge, 2nd Earl of Dartmouth, concluded his long and impactful life at [Blackheath, Kent](/Blackheath,_Kent), on 15 July 1801, reaching the age of 70. His passing marked the end of an era for a statesman who had navigated the turbulent waters of British imperial policy during a period of unprecedented change and colonial upheaval. His remains were interred in [Trinity Church in the Minories](/Church_of_Holy_Trinity,_Minories) on 3 August 1801, a traditional resting place for notable figures of the time.

Upon his death, the earldom, along with its associated titles and responsibilities, passed to his eldest son, [George Legge, 3rd Earl of Dartmouth](/George_Legge,_3rd_Earl_of_Dartmouth). His devoted spouse, Lady Dartmouth, née Frances Catherine Nicholl, survived him by four years, passing away in July 1805. The family's principal residence was [Sandwell Hall](/Sandwell_Hall), a grand country house situated in the picturesque [Sandwell Valley](/Sandwell_Valley). This estate, which stood as a testament to the family's prominence and wealth, has since been demolished, leaving only historical records and the land it once occupied to mark its former glory.

